Singapore Stocks: CapitaLand, Cosco, Hi-P, Keppel, Thai Beverage

-- B y   J o n a t h a n   B u r g o s
-- 
2011-03-16T04:53:36Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-15/capitaland-cosco-keppel-thaibev-singapore-stocks-preview.html
Singapore’s  Straits Times Index (FSSTI) 
gained 0.2 percent to 2,952.25 as of the 12:30 p.m. trading
break. Almost two stocks rose for each that fell in the
benchmark index of 30 companies.  Shares on the measure trade at an average 13.5 times
estimated earnings, compared with about 15.6 times at the end of
2010, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  The following shares were among the most active in the
market. Stock symbols are in parentheses after the company name.    CapitaLand Ltd. (CAPL)  ,  Southeast Asia ’s biggest
developer, gained 0.6 percent to S$3.15. The company said it
sold its entire 50 percent indirect stake in Beijing Red Diamond
Science & Technology Development Ltd. for a cash consideration
of 114 million yuan ($17 million). BRD owns a completed office
building known as IBM China Centre in Beijing.  Cosco Corp. Singapore Ltd. (COS SP): The China-based
shipbuilder declined 1.1 percent to S$1.82. The company said an
Asian shipowner had canceled an order for the construction of a
bulk carrier.    Hi-P International Ltd. (HIP)  , the provider of
electronics-manufacturing services whose clients include Apple
Inc. and BlackBerry-maker Research in Motion Ltd., lost 0.9
percent to S$1.07. Apple said it is delaying the release of the
iPad 2 tablet computer in  Japan  in the aftermath of earthquakes
and a tsunami in the Asian country.  Keppel Corp. (KEP SP), the world’s biggest builder of oil
platforms, increased 0.4 percent to S$11.40. The company said
Japan Drilling Co. ordered a drilling rig, to be delivered in
March 2013, for $210 million.  Thai Beverage Ltd. (THBEV SP), the drinks maker, gained 1.8
percent to 28.5 Singapore cents. The company said it increased
its holding in Yunnan Yulinquan Liquor Co., a Chinese company,
by 24 million yuan.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jonathan Burgos in  Singapore  at 
 jburgos4@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at   ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 